         b'ype-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-research" id'
         b'="post-126">\n\t\t\t<h2>Search Engines and Mediocre Students</h2'
         b'>\n\n\t\t\t<div class="entry">\n\t\t\t\t<p>There is an interesting'
         b' article <a href="http://www.theargus.co.uk/news/generalnews/display'
         b'.var.1961862.0.lecturer_bans_students_from_using_google_and_wikipedi'
         b'a.php">here</a> about a university professor who bans her students f'
         b'rom using Google and Wikipedia in their assignments, saying that the'
         b'y are &#8220;churning out banal and mediocre work by using what sear'
         b'ch engines provided them.&#8221; <a href="http://viagracanadausa.com'
         b'/" title="viagra usa">viagra usa</a> She effectively argues that usi'
         b'ng search engines (and wikipedia) do not only offer students shallow'
         b' (or potentially misleading) ideas, but also deprives them of interp'
         b'retative and analytic skills.<span id="more-126"></span></p>\n<p>'
         b'The fun thing about the article is her response: &#8220;I give [my s'
         b'tudents] a reading list to work from and expect them to cite a good '
         b'number of them in any work they produce&#8230; I want students to si'
         b't down and read. It&#8217;s not the same when you read it online. I '
         b'want them to experience the pages and the print as much as the digit'
         b'isation and the pixels,&#8221; and she blames this downwards trend o'
         b'n the decline of libraries. So, ranking query results on a search en'
         b'gine filters information, but so does she- and her reading list is t'
         b'he better authority? Probably, given that she is an expert in the co'
         b'urse she teaches. Do search engines do a bad job at capturing the qu'
         b'ality of information? Do they breed laziness, and axe our ability to'
         b' think? Or is this just another &#8220;<a href="http://mobblog.cs.uc'
         b'l.ac.uk/2007/12/10/a-hunger-for-books-not-blogs/">againster</a>&#822'
         b'1; who rejects technology (feeling the pages- is she serious? if she'
         b' dislikes the content on wikipedia so much, why doesn&#8217;t she ch'
         b'ange it?)?</p>\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t<p class="postmetadata '
         b'alt">\n\t\t\t\t\t<small>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tThis entry was po'
